    "question": "What would it mean for the phenomenal/access distinction to be *scale-dependent*—i.e., for the same mental content to be "phenomenal" at one temporal or spatial scale (e.g., micro-experiences) but "accessible" at another (e.g., macro-reportable states)? Could this resolve apparent conflicts between first-person and third-person accounts of consciousness?",
    "originality_explanation": "This question is original because it introduces *scale* as a variable in the phenomenal/access debate, which is almost entirely absent in the literature. While some work discusses "microphenomenology" (e.g., Petitmengin), it doesn't explicitly link scale to the access/phenomenal divide. The idea that the same content could shift categories based on scale is novel.",
    "framework_transcendence": "Challenges the assumption that phenomenal and access consciousness are *ontologically distinct* by proposing they are *epistemically relative* to the scale of observation. It transcends both dualist (e.g., Chalmers) and reductionist (e.g., Dennett) frameworks by treating the distinction as a *methodological artifact* rather than a metaphysical one.",
